# Sign in with GitHub

Let your users sign in to Nocturne with their GitHub account. This guide walks through
creating an OAuth App on GitHub and registering it in Nocturne.

## 1. Create a GitHub OAuth App

1. Go to [github.com/settings/developers](https://github.com/settings/developers)
   (or for an organization: **Settings > Developer settings > OAuth Apps**)
2. Click **New OAuth App**
3. Fill in the fields:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **Application name** | `Nocturne` |
| **Homepage URL** | `https://your-instance.com` |
| **Authorization callback URL** | `https://your-instance.com/api/auth/oidc/callback` |

Replace `your-instance.com` with your actual Nocturne domain.

4. Click **Register application**

## 2. Generate a client secret

1. On the app page, click **Generate a new client secret**
2. Copy the **Client ID** and the **Client secret** immediately — the secret is only shown once

<Callout type="warning" title="Save the secret now">
  GitHub only displays the client secret once. If you lose it, you'll need to
  generate a new one.
</Callout>

## 3. Add the provider in Nocturne

1. Sign in to your Nocturne instance as an admin
2. Go to **Settings > Admin > OIDC Providers**
3. Click **Add Provider** and fill in:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **Name** | `GitHub` |
| **Issuer URL** | `https://github.com` |
| **Client ID** | The client ID from step 2 |
| **Client Secret** | The client secret from step 2 |
| **Scopes** | `openid, user:email` |
| **Icon** | `github` |
| **Button Color** | `#24292f` |

4. Click **Save**

The GitHub sign-in button will appear on your login page immediately.

<Callout type="info" title="GitHub as an OIDC provider">
  GitHub doesn't natively implement OpenID Connect discovery, but Nocturne
  handles this automatically. Just use <code>https://github.com</code> as
  the issuer URL — Nocturne knows how to map GitHub's OAuth endpoints and
  retrieve user profile information.
</Callout>

## 4. Test it

1. Open your Nocturne login page in a private/incognito window
2. Click **Sign in with GitHub**
3. Authorize the Nocturne app when prompted by GitHub
4. You should be redirected back to Nocturne and signed in

## GitHub Enterprise

For GitHub Enterprise Server, use your instance's URL as the issuer:

```
https://github.your-company.com
```

The callback URL should still point to your Nocturne instance.
